# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] The **1708 British general election** was the first general election to be held after the Acts of Union had united the Parliaments of England and Scotland.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] The election saw the Whigs gain a majority in the House of Commons, and by November the Whig-dominated parliament had succeeded in pressuring the Queen into accepting the Whig Junto into government for the first time since the late 1690s.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] The Whigs only able to take partial control of the government, however, owing to the continued presence of the moderate Tory Godolphin in the cabinet (as Lord High Treasurer) and the opposition of the Queen.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] Contests were held in 95 of the 269 English and Welsh constituencies and 28 of the 45 Scottish constituencies.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] Following the election, Whig MP Lord Somers was appointed as Lord President of the Council.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] However, moderate Tory Lord Godolphin remained as Lord High Treasurer and the Godolphin–Marlborough ministry remained in place.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] In England, there were 513 MPs elected from 245 constituencies (203 boroughs, 40 counties, and 2 universities).
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] In Wales, there were 24 MPs from 24 constituencies.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] In Scotland, there were 45 MPs from 45 constituencies (30 counties and 15 burghs).
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] The first general election held since the Union took place between 30 April 1708 and 7 July 1708.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] In England and Wales, the Whigs took 268 seats and the Tories took 225, with 20 unclassified.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1708-british-general-election] The 45 in Scotland could be classified as ministerial supporters.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The **1710 British general election** produced a landslide victory for the Tories.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The election came in the wake of the prosecution of Henry Sacheverell, which had led to the collapse of the previous government led by Godolphin and the Whig Junto.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] In November 1709 the clergyman Henry Sacheverell had delivered a sermon fiercely criticising the government's policy of toleration for Protestant dissenters and attacking the personal conduct of the ministers.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The government had Sacheverell impeached, and he was narrowly found guilty but received only a light sentence, making the government appear weak and vindictive.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The trial enraged a large section of the population, and riots in London led to attacks on dissenting places of worship and cries of "Church in Danger".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The government's unpopularity was further increased by its enthusiasm for the war with France, as peace talks with the French king Louis XIV had broken down over the government's insistence that the Bourbons hand over the Spanish throne to the Habsburgs.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The Tories' policy of pursuing peace appealed to a country worn out by constant war.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] Queen Anne, disliking the Junto and sensing that the government could not survive long, gradually replaced it with a Tory ministry throughout the summer of 1710.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The election was bitterly contested in almost all the counties and "open" boroughs, even when a poll was not held.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] Contests occurred in 131 constituencies in England and Wales; approximately half of all English and Welsh constituencies.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The overwhelming Tory victory surprised few, and following the election most remaining Whigs resigned from office.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The new government was led by the moderate Tory Robert Harley who was unpopular among the more partisan Tories.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] Harley's ministry faced increasing pressure from the extremists whose position in Parliament had been enormously strengthened by the result.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] See 1796 British general election for details.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The constituencies used were the same throughout the existence of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The general election was held between 2 October 1710 and 16 November 1710.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1710-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or parliamentary borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1713-british-general-election] The **1713 British general election** was held on 22 August 1713 to 12 November 1713, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1713-british-general-election] It produced further gains for the governing Tory party.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1713-british-general-election] The government remained popular with the electorate, however, having entered into peace negotiations ending the War of the Spanish Succession and later agreeing on the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1713-british-general-election] The Tories consequently made further gains against the Whigs, making Harley's job even more difficult.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1713-british-general-election] Contests were held in 94 constituencies in England and Wales, some 35 per cent of the total, reflecting a decline in partisan tension and the Whigs' belief that they were unlikely to win anyway.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/1713-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 August 1713 and 12 November 1713.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] Douglas was the son of William Douglas of Spynie and his wife Marjorie Menteith, daughter of Patrick Mentieth of Egilsay.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] On 12 April 1688, he married Janet Scot, widow of Alexander Cruickshanks of Waristoun.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] Douglas served as Shire Commissioner for Orkney and Zetland stewartry in the Parliament of Scotland from 1702 to 1707.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] He was knighted in 1707 and was one of the Scottish MPs co-opted to the first Parliament of Great Britain in 1707.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] At the 1708 British general election he was returned as Member of Parliament for Orkney and Shetland and his only known vote was in favour of the impeachment of Henry Sacheverell in 1710.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] He was appointed the Chamberlain of the Bishopric of Orkney in 1710, which brought a salary or pension of £1000 Scots.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] He was reluctant to stand again, but was promised £200 from the government to cover the cost of attendance at Westminster.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] At the 1710 British general election, he was returned as a Tory and listed as a 'worthy patriot' who helped to detect the mismanagements of the previous administration.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] However he never received the promised travel allowance.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] He declined standing at the 1713 British general election.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] He was joint lieutenant of Orkney in 1715.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] Douglas died in January 1718, having had two sons and three daughters.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay] Egilsay descended via his eldest son, William, to his granddaughter, Janet, who married James Baikie of Tankerness and had a son, Robert.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] The **Bishop of Orkney** was the ecclesiastical head of the **Diocese of Orkney**, one of thirteen medieval bishoprics of Scotland.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] It was based for almost all of its history at St Magnus Cathedral, Kirkwall.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] The bishopric appears to have been suffragan of the Archbishop of York (with intermittent control exercised by the Archbishop of Hamburg-Bremen) until the creation of the Archbishopric of Trondheim (*Niðaros*) in 1152.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] Although Orkney itself did not unite with mainland Scotland until 1468, the Scottish kings and political community had been pushing for control of the islands for centuries.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] The see, however, remained under the nominal control of Trondheim until the creation of the Archbishopric of St Andrews in 1472, when it became for the first time an officially Scottish bishopric.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] The Bishopric's links with Rome ceased to exist after the Scottish Reformation.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] The bishopric continued, saving temporary abolition between 1638 and 1661, under the episcopal Church of Scotland until the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] Episcopacy in the established church in Scotland was permanently abolished in 1689, but a Scottish Episcopal Church bishopric encompassing Orkney was created in 1865, as the Bishopric of Aberdeen and Orkney.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/chamberlain-of-the-bishopric-of-orkney] In 1878, the Catholic Church in Scotland re-established the bishopric system, and Orkney came under the resurrected and reformatted Diocese of Aberdeen.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] Unusually for the Northern Isles, it has been suggested that Egilsay may have a partly Gaelic name.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] While at first sight, it appears to be Egil's island, "Egil" being a Norse personal name, the Gaelic *eaglais* (Celtic "eccles") meaning church, may be part of the root, as the island is dominated by a church of pre-Norse foundation.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] The island of Kili Holm just to the north, may represent *cille*, a monastic cell.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] The island's population was 26 as recorded by the 2011 census a drop of almost a third since 2001 when there were 37 usual residents.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] During the same period, Scottish island populations as a whole grew by 4% to 103,702.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] By 2022 the population had declined to 17.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/egilsay] Orkney Ferries sail from the island to Tingwall on the Orkney Mainland via Wyre and Rousay.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] Douglas was a younger son of James Douglas, 10th Earl of Morton, and Anne, daughter of Sir James Hay, 1st Baronet.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] He became a professional soldier in various Scottish regiments but was made redundant in 1707 following the Union of England and Scotland.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] Douglas was elected as Member of Parliament for Lanark Burghs, also known as Linlithgow Burgs, in 1708 and was returned there unopposed in 1710.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] In 1713 he was elected MP for Orkney and Shetland, although this was the first time that the constituency had been contested, usually going to the Morton interest.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] He was returned as MP for Lanark Burghs in 1715 when he was unopposed, but in the 1722 general election he was defeated there in a contest.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] However at the same general election he was also returned unopposed at Orkney where he was returned again in 1727.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] He surrendered his seat in 1730 when he succeeded his elder brother in the earldom and was elected a Scottish representative peer, which he remained until his death.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] He also served as Vice-Admiral of Scotland from 1733 to 1738.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/george-douglas-13th-earl-of-morton] He died in January 1738 and was succeeded in his titles by his son, James.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The son of Joshua Sacheverell, rector of St Peter's, Marlborough, he was adopted by his godfather, Edward Hearst, and his wife after Joshua's death in 1684.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] His maternal grandfather, Henry Smith, after whom he was possibly named, may be the same Henry Smith who is recorded as a signatory of Charles I's death warrant.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] His relations included what he labelled his "fanatic kindred"; his great-grandfather John was a rector, three of whose sons were Presbyterians.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] One of these sons, John (Sacheverell's grandfather), was ejected from his vicarage at the Restoration and died in prison after being convicted for preaching at a Dissenting meeting.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He was more proud of distant relatives who were Midlands landed gentry that had supported the Royalist cause during the Civil War.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Hearsts were pious High Anglicans and were pleased with Sacheverell, who was "always retiring to his private devotions before he went to school".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He was educated at Marlborough Grammar School from 1684 to 1689.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He was sent to Magdalen College, Oxford, in 1689, where he was a student until 1701 and a fellow from 1701 to 1713.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Joseph Addison, another native of Wiltshire, had entered the same college two years earlier.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] It was at Sacheverell's instigation that Addison wrote his *Account of the Greatest English Poets* (1694) and he dedicated it to Sacheverell.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell took his degree of B.A. on 30 June 1693, and became M.A. on 16 May 1695.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Bishop of Oxford, John Hough, ordained him deacon on 18 May 1695.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] However, when, in 1697, he presented himself to the Bishop of Lichfield, William Lloyd, with a reference from the dean of Lichfield, Lloyd complained of his grammatically incorrect Latin.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell, who had published several Latin poems, quoted Latin grammars to verify his Latin and apparently told Lloyd it was "better Latin than he or any of his chaplains could make".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Lloyd sent his secretary to his library to prove Sacheverell wrong but failed to do so.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In 1696, he was appointed chaplain to Sir Charles Holte and curate for Aston parish church.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] However, when the Aston living fell vacant, Holte refused to appoint Sacheverell.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Lancelot Addison, the dean of Lichfield and the father of Joseph, nominated him to the small vicarage of Cannock in Staffordshire and after an intense three-day examination, Lloyd was finally convinced Sacheverell was ready and accepted his nomination in September 1697.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell was threatened with prosecution for seditious libel after preaching a fiery sermon but this was dropped due to Sacheverell's unimportance.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In July 1701, he was elected Fellow of Magdalen College but his overbearing, disrespectful self-confidence and arrogance won him few friends.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In 1709 before his two famous sermons, Thomas Hearne dismissed him as a loud-mouthed wine-soaker.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] However he was a hard worker and an active teacher, being promoted to a variety of offices.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In June 1703, he was appointed to an endowed lectureship; in 1703 he was appointed College Librarian; in 1708 was appointed Senior Dean of Arts and in 1709 he became Bursar.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell first achieved notability as a High Church preacher in May 1702 when he gave a sermon entitled *The Political Union*, on the necessity of the union between church and state, and denigrating Dissenters, occasional conformists and their Whig supporters.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] His peroration included an appeal to Anglicans not to "strike sail to a party which is an open and avowed enemy to our communion" but instead to "hang out the bloody flag and banner of defiance".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Gaining a small London readership, Daniel Defoe labelled Sacheverell "the bloody flag officer" and in his *The Shortest Way with the Dissenters* he included in its subtitle an acknowledgement of "Mr Sach—ll's sermon and others".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] John Dennis also replied to Sacheverell in *The Danger of Priestcraft to Religion and Government*.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Roger Mander, Vice-Chancellor of Oxford, appointed Sacheverell to preach the University Sermon on 10 June 1702, the date chosen by Queen Anne as a Fast Day for Heaven's blessing for British success in the new war against France.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In support of the Tory candidate at the 1702 English general election, Sir John Pakington, 4th Baronet, Sacheverell published *The Character of a Low-Church-Man*.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] This attacked William Lloyd and advised the clergy to be on the look out against "false brethren" within the Church.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Pakington was grateful and recommended Sacheverell to Robert Harley as Speaker's chaplain.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Harley, a moderate Tory with a Dissenting background, declined.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Only two other sermons in this period were printed: *The Nature and Mischief of Prejudice and Partiality* (1704) and *The Nature, Guilt and Danger of Presumptuous Sins* (1708).
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] With two other Oxford dons he wrote *The Rights of the Church of England Asserted and Proved* (1705).
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The first sermon led to a further notice by Defoe that "Mr Sacheverell of Oxford has blown his second trumpet to let us know he has not yet taken down his bloody flag".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] During the "Church in Danger" scare of 1705-06 he preached a sermon in which he (according to Hearne) with "a great deal of courage and boldness" showed "the great danger the Church is in ... from the fanatics and other false brethren, whom he set forth in their proper colours".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In July 1708 he was awarded a Doctorate of Divinity, possibly due to his abilities as a preacher as well as for his teaching.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In March 1709 a local brewer named John Lade suggested to Sacheverell that he put himself forward for the vacant office of chaplain at St Saviour's, Southwark.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He campaigned for the post with such vigour that a fellow clergyman wrote "None is so much talked of as he all over the Town.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] I suppose we shall have him very speedily the subject of de Foe's *Review*, in which he has formerly had the honour of being substantially abused".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] His most notable backers were Lord Weymouth and Sir William Trumbull.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] News of his candidacy alarmed the Archbishop of Canterbury, Thomas Tenison, and aroused opposition from the Dissenters, as Trumbull's nephew wrote: "[They] give out that if they can keep him out this time, they shall for ever keep him from coming into the City".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] However Sacheverell was appointed by 28 votes to 19 on 24 May.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell soon stirred up more controversy by printing a sermon he had been invited to deliver at Derby Assizes on 15 August, entitled *The Communication of Sin*.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The new Lord Mayor of London, Sir Samuel Garrard, 4th Baronet, was a zealous Tory and it was his responsibility to appoint the preacher for the annual 5 November sermon to the City Fathers at St Paul's Cathedral to commemorate the failure of the Gunpowder Plot.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Garrard later claimed no acquaintance with Sacheverell, knowing him only by reputation.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Whigs later claimed that Sacheverell was hired as a tool of the Tory party to deliver the sermon.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The historian Geoffrey Holmes claims there is no evidence for this as Sacheverell's papers were destroyed after his death but that it was in Sacheverell's character to deliver the sermon off his own bat.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell's audience included thirty clergymen and a large number of Jacobites and Nonjurors.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Prior to the sermon, prayers and hymns were delivered.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] A witness saw Sacheverell, sitting with the clergy, working himself up into an angry mood, describing "the fiery red that overspread his face ... and the goggling wildness of his eyes ... he came into the pulpit like a Sybil to the mouth of her cave".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The title of his sermon, *The Perils of False Brethren, in Church, and State*, derived from 2 Corinthians 11:26.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The 5 November was an important day in the Whig calendar, both the day of the Gunpowder Plot of 5 November 1605 and William of Orange's landing at Torbay on 5 November 1688.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Whigs claimed both these days as a double deliverance from "popery".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell compared the Gunpowder Plot not to 1688 but to the date of the execution of Charles I, 30 January 1649.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell claimed that these two events demonstrated the "rage and bloodthirstiness of both the popish and fanatick enemies of our Church and Government...
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] These TWO DAYS indeed are but one united proof and visible testimonial of the same dangerous and rebellious principles these confederates in iniquity maintain".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The threat to the Church from Catholics was dealt with in three minutes; the rest of the one-and-a-half-hour sermon was an attack on Dissenters and the "false brethren" who aided them in menacing church and state.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Then there were those who wanted to change the worship of the Church, the latitudinarians who promoted toleration and denied that schism was sinful, taking "all occasions to comply with the dissenters both in public and private affairs, as persons of tender consciences and piety".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] But certainly they are the greatest enemies of that, and his late Majesty, and the most ungrateful for the deliverance, who endeavour to cast such black and odious colours upon both".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He attacked Dissenting academies as places where "all the Hellish principles of fanaticism, regicide and anarchy are openly professed and taught" and attacked occasional conformity as giving disloyal elements bases of official power.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] These false brethren were working to "weaken, undermine and betray in themselves, and encourage and put it in the power of our professed enemies to overturn and destroy, the constitution and establishment of both".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In due course the Church would lose its character and become a "heterogeneous mixture" united only by Protestantism.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He then claimed that "this spurious and villainous notion, which will take in Jews, Quakers, Mahometans and anything, as well as Christians".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] This had been tried when the Church's enemies had advocated Comprehension and now the same people were using "Moderation and Occasional Conformity" to destroy the defences of the Church.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The end result would be an Erastian state of affairs where people became nonplussed about questions of faith and fall prey to "universal scepticism and infidelity".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Occasionally Conforming Dissenters Sacheverell saw as the enemy within.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] I pray God we may be out of danger, but we may remember the King's person was voted to be so at the same time that his murderers were conspiring his death".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell pointed to the sinfulness of the false brethren.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] For Anglicans holding office it was a betrayal of their oaths; secondly, it was an example of hypocrisy and disregarding of principle for material gain.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He said it was a "vast scandal and offence ... to see men of characters and stations thus shift and prevaricate with their principles", like Christ's disciples when Christ's life was at stake.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He attacked "the crafty insidiousness of such wily Volpones".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] "Volpone" was the nickname of Sidney Godolphin, a Tory who had allied himself with the Whig Junto and who had been attacked by Tories as an apostate.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The prospect for these false brethren, Sacheverell claimed, was to take "his portion with hypocrites and unbelievers, with all liars, that have their part in the lake which burns with fire and brimstone".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell ended the sermon by exhorting Anglicans to close ranks, to present "an army of banners to our enemies" and hope that the false brethren "would throw off the mask, entirely quit the Church of which they are no true members, and not fraudulently eat her bread and lay wait for her ruin".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] High-ranking clergy must excommunicate offenders "and let any power on earth dare reverse a sentence ratified in Heaven".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] A long battle lay ahead for the Church Militant, "against principalities, against powers, against the rulers of the darkness of this world, against spiritual wickedness in high places".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] That the battle would be hard was accepted "because her adversaries are chief and her enemies at present prosper".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] To Him be glory and dominion for ever and ever.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] As Sacheverell left St Paul's and travelled through the City, he was cheered by a crowd.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The joke doing the rounds was that "St Paul's was on fire a Saturday".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell prepared the sermon for publication and consulted three lawyers, who all claimed it breached neither common nor civil law.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 25 November the sermon was printed, the first edition being 500 copies.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 1 December the second edition came off the press and numbered between 30,000 and 40,000 copies.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] By the end of Sacheverell's trial, an estimated 100,000 copies of his sermon were in circulation.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] A conservative estimate of the readership, 250,000 people, was equal to the whole electorate of Britain at that time.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] This had no parallel in early eighteenth-century Britain.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] For the first few weeks, many Whigs believed that the sermon was beneath official response.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Defoe wrote that "the roaring of this beast ought to give you no manner of disturbance.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] You ought to laugh at him, let him alone; he'll vent his gall, and then he'll be quiet".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Within three days of the sermon being on sale, pamphlet responses were being printed.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] George Ridpath's *The Peril of Being Zealously Affected, but not Well* attacked Sacheverell, as did White Kennett's *True Answer*.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Whig author of *High Church Display'd* claimed that Sacheverell "and his party were entirely routed in those paper-skirmishes".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] It took six weeks before a pamphlet defence of Sacheverell was published, and thereafter they became numerous.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On the last Sunday of November Sacheverell preached at St Margaret's, Lothbury.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The church was packed to full attendance, with an enormous crowd outside threatening to break open the church for a chance to hear him preach.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] With his sermon now in massive circulation, the Whig government considered prosecuting Sacheverell.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He had also attacked a leading member of the government, Godolphin.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] However, when the government lawyers examined the sermon, they discovered that Sacheverell had chosen his words carefully to such an extent that they considered it uncertain whether he could be prosecuted for sedition.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] They considered bringing Sacheverell to the Commons' Bar on the charge of displaying contempt for the Commons resolution of December 1705.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] A vote in the Commons would be enough to convict him.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] However this approach would deny the Whigs the publicity they sought in prosecuting Sacheverell and he would be at liberty once the Commons' session ended.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Whigs wanted a punishment sufficient to deter other High Churchmen.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] A vote in the House of Lords on a charge of high crimes and misdemeanours had the power to achieve what the Whigs wanted and could also inflict a heavy fine with confiscation of goods and imprisonment for life.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 13 December the Commons ordered Sacheverell to attend the Bar of the House.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 14 December Sacheverell appeared before the Commons with a hundred other clergymen also in attendance to show moral support.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The House resolved that Sacheverell be impeached and he was put into the custody of the Serjeant-at-Arms.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He was visited at his lodgings in Peters Street by prominent Tories such as the Duke of Leeds, Lord Rochester and Duke of Buckingham.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Duke of Beaufort sent him claret and 50 guineas.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Although the Tories in the Commons managed only 64 votes on behalf of Sacheverell's petition for bail, there was an outbreak of support for him amongst the Anglican clergy.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Duke of Marlborough remarked that "the whole body of the inferior clergy espouse his interest".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell's impeachment trial lasted from 27 February to 21 March 1710 and the verdict was that he should be suspended for three years and that the two sermons should be burnt at the Royal Exchange.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] This was the decree of the state, and it made him a martyr in the eyes of the populace and bringing about the first Sacheverell riots that year in London and the rest of the country, which included attacks on Presbyterian and other Dissenter places of worship, with some being burned down.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The rioting in turn led to the downfall of the government ministry later that year and the passing of the Riot Act in 1714.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The tide of public opinion had turned in Sacheverell's favour and the people viewed his light punishment as a deliverance for the whole Church of England.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He became "the saviour of the Church and the nation's martyr-hero".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] From 21–23 March almost all major streets in Westminster and west London celebrated by bonfires, illuminated windows and toasts to Sacheverell and the Queen accompanied by the ringing of church bells.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Trained Bands had to be called out due to growing disturbances and in Southwark a new riot was not ended until after 30 March.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Across the country there were celebrations in support for Sacheverell, with bonfires, illuminated windows and the ringing of church bells.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] When Sacheverell went to thank the peers who had voted for him who were still in London, "he was huzza'd by the mob like a prize-fighter".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Despite the suspension from preaching, Sacheverell was presented to a living in Shropshire on 26 June 1710 as Rector of Selattyn near Oswestry by a former university student of his, Robert Lloyd, local landowner and later an MP for Shropshire.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell travelled to Selattyn in June in what Holmes called "the most extraordinary Progress ever made by a private individual in Britain".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Richard Steele wrote that "the anarchic fury ran so high that Harry Sacheverell swelling, and Jack Huggins laughing, marched through England in a triumph more than military".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 15 May he left London for Oxford with a cavalcade of 66 horsemen, increasing to 300 by the time he reached Uxbridge, with hundreds more when he went through Beaconsfield, High Wycombe and West Wycombe.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] When he reached Wheatley near Oxford, Lord Abingdon, the local MP Thomas Rowney, noblemen, Heads of Houses, the Proctors, most Oxford Fellows and others welcomed Sacheverell to Oxford University.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] This included twelve towns and he was honoured with ten civic receptions.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He was given fifty vast dinners, numerable lavish suppers, including at least 22 private dinners.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Their hosts included Lord Denbigh at Newnham Paddox, Lord Leigh at Stoneleigh Abbey, Lord Willoughby de Broke, Lord Kilmorey, Lord Folliot, William Bromley at Baginton, Sir William Boughton at Lawford Park, Sir Edward Cobb, Sir Edward Aston and Sir Charles Holte at Aston.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell and his entourage spent only seven nights in local inns as Tory landowners put their houses at his disposal.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He spent ten days with Lord Craven at Coombe Abbey, then went to New Hall Manor owned by his kinsman George Sacheverell.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] At every house he stayed, local gentry and clergy paid him homage.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell was also attended by the multitude.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] At Coventry, 5000 people welcomed him into the city.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] At Birmingham he was greeted by 300-500 horse and 3000–4000 foot.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Between 5000 and 7000 greeted him at Shrewsbury headed by an enormous cavalcade of gentry and yeomen.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The church bells rang from five in the morning until eleven at night.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] At Bridgnorth, 64 clergymen, 3500 horse and 3000 foot welcomed him.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 19 July Sacheverell returned to Oxford.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] By 8 August, the date of Godolphin's dismissal, there had been sent to the Queen 97 Tory addresses couched in High Church Anglican language.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 30 June the Bishop of Worcester William Lloyd wrote of "the great danger we are brought into by the turbulent preaching and practices of an impudent man ... now riding in triumph over the middle of England, everywhere stirring up the people to address to her Majesty for a new Parliament.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The danger is so great that I cannot but tremble to think of it, if her Majesty should dissolve the present Parliament and change her ministry, which is the thing driven at by the addresses".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The general election held in October/November 1710 was fought by the Tory-Anglican clergy and gentry on the same platform which Sacheverell stood seven months before.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In Cornwall the two victorious Tory candidates, John Trevanion and George Granville, were swept to victory on the back of the chant: "Trevanion and Granville, sound as a bell/For the Queen, the Church, and Sacheverell".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Only ten managers of Sacheverell's prosecution were re-elected and Tories circulated division lists of those who had voted for or against Sacheverell.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] His influence was all-pervasive, being linked to the safety of the Church and on the lips of election mobs, with his portrait being a favourite emblem of Tories.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The election was a personal triumph for Sacheverell as well as a Tory landslide, with the anti-Whig reaction especially marked in counties where Sacheverell had passed during his Progress.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell's sentence expired on 23 March 1713.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The reaction in London was muted compared to the celebrations in the provincial towns such as Worcester, Norwich, Wells and Frome where the steeples were decked with flags, windows were decorated with streamers along with bonfires and people singing in the streets.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 29 March Sacheverell preached at St Saviour's for the first time since his ban expired and the enormous crowd who came to see him was described as "inconceivable to those who did not see it, and inexpressible to those who did".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He took as his text Luke 23:34, "Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do" and titled it *The Christian Triumph: or The Duty of Praying for our Enemies*.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Despite the provocative title, as White Kennett wrote, "there was little mischief in it" and it sold only half the 30,000 copies printed.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Jonathan Swift called it a "long dull sermon".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 13 April 1713 it was announced he was to be instituted to the valuable rectory of St Andrew's, Holborn.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 29 May 1713 he was appointed to preach the sermon for the anniversary of the Restoration at the House of Commons, titled *False Notions of Liberty in Religion and Government destructive of both*.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He attacked his Whig persecutors as "traitorous, heady and high-minded men" and upheld the doctrine of non-resistance.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In December 1713 he preached at St Paul's to the Corporation for the Sons of the Clergy but his procession was hissed by the crowd at the Royal Exchange.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Upon the death of Queen Anne and the accession of the first Hanoverian monarch George I, the Duke of Marlborough made a public procession back to London.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell achieved renewed fame by attacking this as "an unparalleled insolence and a vile trampling upon royal ashes".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] When the London clergy presented loyal addresses to the new king at court in September, Sacheverell was sent away by vocal attacks by Whigs and "getting to the outward door, the footmen hissed him on a long lane on both sides till he got into a coach".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell left London and went on a new Progress through Oxford, Wiltshire and Warwickshire.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] An outbreak of rioting occurred in protest against George's coronation in October and Sacheverell's name was extolled by the rioters.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] At Bristol the crowd shouted "Sacheverell and Ormond, and damn all foreigners!"; in Taunton they cried "Church and Dr.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell"; at Birmingham, "Kill the old Rogue [King George], Kill them all, Sacheverell for ever"; at Tewkesbury, "Sacheverell for ever, Down with the Roundheads"; at Shrewsbury, "High Church and Sacheverell for ever".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In Dorchester and Nuneaton, Sacheverell's health was drunk.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The Bishop of London, John Robinson, ordered him back to Holborn and warned him against politicking.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] During the general election held in January–March 1715, the slogan "High Church and Sacheverell" was used by Tories.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In the aftermath of the heavy Tory defeat, Sacheverell may have flirted with Jacobitism but he did not take up the invitation from the Pretender's court in Rome that he should settle there.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Another set of rioting broke out in the spring and summer of 1715.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On the anniversary of Anne's succession, 8 March, the mob at St Andrew's burned a picture of William of Orange, broke windows which were not illuminated in celebration and proposed "to sing the Second Part of the *Sacheverell-Tune*, by pulling down [Dissenting] Meeting Houses".
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] They were persuaded not to do so, however.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] On 10 June the Dissenting chapel in Cross Street, Manchester was sacked by a mob chanting Sacheverell's name.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In May 1717 a riot broke out in Oxford when the Whig Constitution Club tried to burn Sacheverell in effigy, which was prevented by the mob.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Sacheverell inherited the manor of Callow in Derbyshire in the summer of 1715 after George Sacheverell died.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He married George's widow Mary in June 1716 and took possession of the estate in 1717.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He purchased a landed estate in Wilden, Bedfordshire and in 1720 bought an elegant house in South Grove, Highgate, London.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] In January 1723 he slipped on the icy doorstep of his Highgate home and broke two ribs.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Henry Sacheverell died at his Highgate house on 5 June 1724.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] He was buried at St Andrew's in the vault.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] The house was later occupied by the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge, and is now owned by Kate Moss.
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Writing later in the eighteenth century, the Whig member of parliament Edmund Burke used the speeches of Whig leaders at the Sacheverell trial in his *An Appeal from the New to the Old Whigs* (1791) to demonstrate true Whiggism (as opposed to the beliefs of the Foxite 'New Whigs').
[src:alexander-douglas-of-eagleshay/henry-sacheverell] Historian Greg Jenner asserts in his *Dead Famous: An Unexpected History of Celebrity from Bronze Age to Silver Screen* (2020, W&N ISBN 978-0297869801) that Sacheverell was the first example of a celebrity.
